1. Convert the given capacitance from picofarads to Farads:
   C = 5.5 pF = 5.5 \times 10^{-12} F

2. Convert the energy loss per alpha particle per second from million electron volts to electron volts per second:
   E = 4.0 million eV/s = 4.0 \times 10^6 eV/s

3. Calculate the change in voltage (V):
   V = V_initial - V_final
   V = 205 V - 195 V = 10 V

4. Calculate the average voltage term for the energy change in the capacitor, which is part of the given time formula:
   (V_initial + V_final) / 2 = (205 V + 195 V) / 2 = 400 V / 2 = 200 V

5. Calculate the total Power (P) dissipated by N alpha particles. The conversion factor for eV to Joules is 1.602 \times 10^{-19} J/eV.
   P = N \times E \times (1.602 \times 10^{-19} J/eV)
   P = 110 \times (4.0 \times 10^6 \text{ eV/s}) \times (1.602 \times 10^{-19} \text{ J/eV})
   P = 110 \times 4.0 \times 1.602 \times 10^{(6 - 19)} \text{ W}
   P = 440 \times 1.602 \times 10^{-13} \text{ W}
   P = 704.88 \times 10^{-13} \text{ W}
   P = 7.0488 \times 10^{-11} \text{ W}

6. Use the given formula for Time (t) to find how long it takes for the potential to diminish:
   t = C \times ((V_initial + V_final) / 2) \times (V_initial - V_final) / \text{Power}
   t = (5.5 \times 10^{-12} \text{ F}) \times (200 \text{ V}) \times (10 \text{ V}) / (7.0488 \times 10^{-11} \text{ W})
   t = (5.5 \times 200 \times 10) \times 10^{-12} / (7.0488 \times 10^{-11}) \text{ seconds}
   t = 11000 \times 10^{-12} / (7.0488 \times 10^{-11}) \text{ seconds}
   t = 1.1 \times 10^4 \times 10^{-12} / (7.0488 \times 10^{-11}) \text{ seconds}
   t = 1.1 \times 10^{-8} / (7.0488 \times 10^{-11}) \text{ seconds}
   t = (1.1 / 7.0488) \times 10^{(-8 - (-11))} \text{ seconds}
   t = (1.1 / 7.0488) \times 10^3 \text{ seconds}
   t = 0.15605777423087399... \times 1000 \text{ seconds}
   t = 156.05777423087399 \text{ seconds}

